# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: comet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea has a nearly spherical shape, with two known craters about 100 and 180 km (62 and 112 mi) in diameter.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Because of its shape and large size, some researchers consider Hygiea a possible dwarf planet.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea has a dark, carbonaceous surface consisting of hydrated and ammoniated silicate minerals, with carbonates and water ice.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea's subsurface likely contains a large fraction of water ice.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] These characteristics make Hygiea very similar to the main-belt dwarf planet Ceres, which suggests the two objects have similar origins and evolutionary histories.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea is the parent body of the Hygiea family, an asteroid family comprising over 7,000 known asteroids that share similar orbital and compositional characteristics with Hygiea.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The Hygiea family is believed to have formed by a giant impact on Hygiea about 2 to 3 billion years ago.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] This impact is thought to have shattered Hygiea, which led to its reaccumulation as a nearly spherical body.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea was discovered on the evening of 12 April 1849 by Italian astronomer Annibale de Gasparis at the Astronomical Observatory of Capodimonte in Naples, Italy.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] On that night he was using the observatory's Reichenbach equatorial telescope to observe a section of the sky in the 12th hour of right ascension, as part of his larger project of cataloguing stars along the ecliptic up to the 14th apparent magnitude.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] While comparing his observations to the Berlin Academy's star chart, de Gasparis noticed a starlike object between magnitude 9 and 10 which was not recorded before.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Although poor weather prevented further observations for a few days, de Gasparis reobserved the object on 14 and 17 April and confirmed it had moved between these dates.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Judging by how much the object had moved, de Gasparis concluded it must be another new planet between the orbit of Mars and Jupiter.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] De Gasparis announced his discovery to Erasmo Fabri Scarpellini, secretary of the *Correspondenza Scientifica* bulletin at Rome, Italy, who in turn passed on the news to Heinrich Christian Schumacher, who published it in the *Astronomische Nachrichten* journal on 11 May 1849.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea was the first asteroid discovered by de Gasparis and the tenth asteroid discovered in history.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] He would later discover another six asteroids between 1850 and 1853 and two more during the 1860s.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] De Gasparis invited Ernesto Capocci Belmonte, his friend and director of the Capodimonte Observatory, to assign a name to the asteroid as gratitude for his help and advice.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Capocci suggested the name *Igea*—the Italian spelling of Hygieia, the Greek goddess of health and daughter of Asclepius.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] De Gasparis added the adjective *Borbonica* to Capocci's suggested name, to honor King Ferdinand II of the Bourbons of Naples who ruled the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies and supported the work of the Capodimonte Observatory.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Together, de Gasparis and Capocci proposed the name *Igea Borbonica* ("Bourbon Hygieia") in a letter forwarded to Ferdinand II on 8 May 1849.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] De Gasparis's commemoration of the Bourbons may have helped him and Capocci circumvent punishment for their participation in the liberal movements of 1848.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The name *Igea Borbonica* was not mentioned in the first communications to the European scientific community.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] When English astronomer John Herschel received the news of Hygiea's discovery from his Neapolitan colleagues, he suggested that Parthenope would be an apt name for de Gasparis's discovery, as it comes from the siren who founded Naples in Greek mythology.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Herschel corresponded with other European scientists and astronomers to hear their thoughts on the name Parthenope for de Gasparis's discovery, although by the time he reached out to de Gasparis, Hygiea had already been named one month earlier.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] When Schumacher, editor of *Astronomische Nachrichten*, learned of the name proposed by de Gasparis and Capocci, he complained in a letter addressed to Herschel on 26 June 1849 that it had the Italian spelling instead of the Latin form, as conventionally done for all the other planets.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Regardless, de Gasparis recognized Herschel's suggestion and expressed desire to realize Herschel's wish.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] On 11 May 1850, de Gasparis discovered the asteroid 11 Parthenope and acknowledged Herschel for the name in his announcement.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] There are multiple variations on the Latin spelling of Hygiea, including *Hygièa*, *Hygia*, and *Hygea*.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The modern English form *Hygiea* is a less common variant of the goddess's name, which in Greek is Ὑγίεια (*Hygieia*) or Ὑγεῖα (*Hygeia*).
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The name was often spelled *Hygeia* (and occasionally *Hygea*) by astronomers during the early 1850s, though by the 1860s, the spelling *Hygiea* became commonplace.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] According to the English astronomer John Russell Hind, the adjective *Borbonica* had been dropped by 1852.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] As with the other previously discovered asteroids, Hygiea was given an astronomical symbol as a way of representing it.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The serpent, particularly when drinking from a bowl, is a traditional symbol of the goddess Hygieia (cf.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] American astronomer Benjamin Apthorp Gould interpreted Hygiea's symbol as a rod of Asclepius, depicting it as a serpent coiled around a staff in a January 1852 publication of the *Astronomical Journal*: (rod of Asclepius) (U+2695 ⚕).
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Both symbols of Hygiea soon became obsolete, as the number of asteroids discovered had grown too much for each to have unique symbols.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] In 1851 Johann Franz Encke proposed a different identification system, suggesting using a number corresponding to the order of discovery enclosed in a small circle—for Hygiea it would be ⑩.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Astronomers began adopting Encke's circled number scheme in scientific publications, though as the number of asteroids discovered grew, astronomers eventually switched to enclosing the number in parentheses, which became the modern minor-planet designation scheme.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] In the case of Hygiea, its modern minor planet designation would be *(10) Hygiea* or *10 Hygiea*.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The Minor Planet Center uses the minor planet provisional designations *A849 GA* and *A900 GA* for Hygiea, though these are only retrospective extensions of the new-style provisional designation scheme established in 1925.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] While the provisional designation A849 GA refers to the discovery date of Hygiea, the designation A900 GA refers to the date when Hygiea was serendipitously observed and catalogued (as *Arequipa 38*) by the Harvard College Observatory's photographic sky survey at Arequipa, Peru in 1900.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea has seen some minor astrological use, though its symbol was confused once again, with Asclepsius's rod replaced by Mercury's caduceus: (Astrological symbol for Hygiea), though in a more elaborate form (U+2BDA ⯚) than the caduceus symbol of the planet Mercury.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The caduceus has long been mistaken for the rod of Asclepius (see caduceus as a symbol of medicine).
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea was referred to as a *planet* in the following years after its discovery, though by 1852 astronomers have also called Hygiea a *minor planet* or an *asteroid*.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] These terms were introduced prior to Hygiea's discovery and became more used with the discovery of more asteroids beginning in the 1850s.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] From the second half of the 19th century, asteroids began to be treated in a predominantly collective way, grouped according to orbital or spectral characteristics, with less attention to the individual object.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Since 2019, telescope images have resolved Hygiea's nearly spherical shape, suggesting that it may have reached hydrostatic equilibrium.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Because Hygiea already orbits the Sun and is located in the asteroid belt where it has not cleared its orbital neighborhood, Hygiea's nearly spherical shape could qualify it as a dwarf planet, according to Pierre Vernazza and collaborators who studied Hygiea with telescope imaging.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] If so, Hygiea could be the smallest dwarf planet known.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] However, the IAU has not yet officially classified Hygiea as a dwarf planet.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea orbits the Sun at an average distance (semi-major axis) of 3.14 astronomical units (AU; 470 million km or 290 million mi), which places it in the outer portion of the main asteroid belt between Mars and Jupiter.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea has an orbital period of 5.57 Earth years and follows an elliptical orbit where its distance from the Sun ranges between 2.79 AU (420 million km; 260 million mi) at perihelion to 3.49 AU (520 million km; 320 million mi) at aphelion.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea has a relatively low orbital inclination of 3.8° with respect to the ecliptic plane.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] In its current orbit, Hygiea never comes closer than 1.24 AU (186 million km; 115 million mi) to Mars and 1.54 AU (230 million km; 143 million mi) to Jupiter.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea is in a three-body mean motion orbital resonance with Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] In this resonance, the mean motions or orbital frequencies of Jupiter, Saturn, and Hygiea follow the relation $8n_{\rm {Jupiter}}-4n_{\rm {Saturn}}-3n_{\rm {Hygiea}}=0$ , where a linear combination of their mean motions ( n ) with integer coefficients equals zero.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Simulations show that this three-body resonance leads to a chaotic evolution in Hygiea's orbit, with a short Lyapunov time between 14,000 and 16,000 years.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] This means that changes in Hygiea's orbit become exponentially less predictable over this time scale.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Other asteroids occasionally pass close to Hygiea, sometimes close enough that their trajectories become visibly perturbed or deflected by Hygiea's gravity.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] This allows astronomers to measure Hygiea's mass.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] A 2002 study identified 40 known asteroids that have passed within 0.05 AU (7.5 million km; 4.6 million mi) of Hygiea between 1970 and 2000.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Over a time span of 30 million years, Hygiea's gravitational perturbations can cause the proper semi-major axes of close-passing asteroids to change by 0.000908 AU (136,000 km; 84,400 mi).
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The Hygiea family is the most populous asteroid family in the outer main belt, and is believed to have formed by a giant impact on Hygiea that ejected at least 1.7% of the asteroid's original mass about 2 to 3 billion years ago.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The impactor that formed the Hygiea family was probably between 75 and 150 km (47 and 93 mi) in diameter.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea contains almost all the mass (over 98%) of the family.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The rotation period of Hygiea is about 13.83 hours (13 hours and 49.5 minutes), with an uncertainty of 0.2 seconds.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] This rotation period was determined via direct imaging and analysis of Hygiea's light curve, or changes in brightness over time.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] From Earth, Hygiea's brightness periodically fluctuates by up to 15% from its average value as albedo features on Hygiea's surface rotate in and out of view.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The north pole of Hygiea's rotation axis points toward the ecliptic south, in the direction of ecliptic longitude 306°±3° and ecliptic latitude −29°±3°.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] This means Hygiea's rotation axis is highly tilted with an obliquity of 120° with respect to the ecliptic.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Since Hygiea's obliquity is greater than 90°, it has a retrograde rotation, meaning it rotates backwards with respect to the direction of its orbit around the Sun.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Before it was directly imaged by telescopes in 2017–2018, Hygiea was thought to have a rotation period twice as long as the currently accepted value.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The first measurements of Hygiea's rotation period beginning in the 1950s reported 18 hours while studies from 1991 and onward reported 27.6 hours.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] These past observations did not collect enough datapoints to produce reliable light curves, which led to these inaccurate rotation period measurements.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea is the fourth-largest main-belt asteroid by both volume and mass, with a volume-equivalent mean diameter of 433 ± 8 km (269 ± 5 mi) and a mass of (8.74±0.69)×1019 kg.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Compared to the largest asteroid Ceres, Hygiea is less than half its diameter and is roughly 10% as massive.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea constitutes 3% of the total mass of the entire main belt and is the largest asteroid in the outer main belt.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The four largest asteroids (Ceres, Pallas, Vesta, and Hygiea) together make up a little more than half of the entire main belt's mass.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] These four largest asteroids have sometimes been collectively referred to as the "Big Four" by astronomers, although historically this term meant the first four asteroids discovered (Ceres, Pallas, Juno, and Vesta).
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea was not recognized as the fourth-largest asteroid until 1974, when David Morrison measured its diameter and albedo for the first time by using its infrared thermal emission.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The best estimate for Hygiea's diameter was measured via direct imaging using the Very Large Telescope (VLT) in Chile, whose atmospheric turbulence-correcting adaptive optics could resolve the asteroid in high angular resolution.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea's mass was measured by observing how its gravity deflects the paths of other asteroids that pass near it.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] This requires an extensive number of observations with accurate positional measurements of the deflected asteroid before and after its close approach.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The measurement of Hygiea's mass through this method was first attempted in 1986, with the analysis of a past close approach by the asteroid 829 Academia (which passed 0.006 AU or 900 thousand km or 560 thousand mi from Hygiea on 19 May 1927).
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea's mass has since been refined with additional asteroid close approaches and more accurate observations.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea is a nearly spherical or ellipsoidal object whose diametric dimensions are 450 km × 430 km × 424 km (280 mi × 267 mi × 263 mi), with an uncertainty of ±10 km (6.2 mi) for the equatorial axes and ±20 km (12 mi) for the polar axis.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] It is the second-most spherical main-belt asteroid after Ceres.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The nearly spherical shape of Hygiea suggests it may be in hydrostatic equilibrium, having attained its shape by its own gravity.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Specifically, Hygiea's polar flattening and specific angular momentum closely matches that of a Maclaurin spheroid, which is the shape assumed by a rotating self-gravitating fluid in hydrostatic equilibrium.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] In contrast to the larger asteroid Vesta, Hygiea lacks large impact craters or basins that would otherwise deform its shape from a sphere.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Only two craters on Hygiea have been confidently identified in VLT imaging, with their respective diameters being 180 ± 15 km (111.8 ± 9.3 mi) and 97 ± 10 km (60.3 ± 6.2 mi).
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Both craters appear to have central peaks.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Vernazza and collaborators who studied these images have informally named the larger crater "Serpens" and smaller crater "Calix", after the Latin words for 'snake' and 'cup', respectively.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] These names, which are not approved by the IAU, were chosen because their eponyms commonly appear in symbols of Hygiea.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Besides Serpens and Calix, VLT images of Hygiea show no obvious or bowl-shaped craters larger than 30 km (19 mi) in diameter.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Ceres similarly lacks large bowl-shaped craters and is instead dominated by flat-floored complex craters, which are difficult to see from Earth—this may be the case for Hygiea.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] An abundance of flat-floored craters on Hygiea could indicate a water ice-rich subsurface, which would allow for the relaxation of its surface topography.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Although Hygiea lacks major impact basins, the existence of the Hygiea family points to a major collisional event in its past.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Rather than leaving a giant impact basin like on Vesta, the impact is thought to have completely shattered Hygiea, which erased all of its pre-existing surface features.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Simulations of the giant impact show that most of Hygiea's debris reaccumulated into a fluid-like body, which was able to relax into a sphere by its own gravity.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The present-day shape of Hygiea suggests it solidified around four hours after the impact.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Other large asteroids that are parents of asteroid families, such as 8 Flora and 31 Euphrosyne, have also been found to show roughly spherical shapes and are thus believed to have undergone similar collisional disruption and reaccumulation.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The surface of Hygiea is dark, with an average visual geometric albedo estimated between 6.3% and 7.2%.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The apparent brightness or reflectance varies across Hygiea's surface due to variations in albedo and shadows cast by topographic features.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] VLT images of Hygiea show several bright spots on its surface, with the brightest one located on Hygiea's southern hemisphere at longitude 290° and latitude −30°.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The brightest spot is 10% brighter than the average reflectance of Hygiea's surface.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] A large dark region is present along Hygiea's equator at longitude 60° and latitude 0°, though it is most likely a shadowed region.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The albedo and reflectance variation across Hygiea's surface resembles those of Ceres.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The temperature on Hygiea's surface depends on the asteroid's rotation, distance from the Sun, and the properties of its surface regolith.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] While the surface of Hygiea have been observed to reach temperatures as high as 230 K (−43 °C; −46 °F) at the subsolar point, the surface cools down as it rotates away from the Sun, which averages out the temperature.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Between Hygiea's perihelion and aphelion distances, the average temperature can range from 150 to 180 K (−123 to −93 °C; −190 to −136 °F).
[src:comet/10-hygiea] At Hygiea's semi-major axis, the average temperature would be 163 K (−110 °C; −166 °F).
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Astronomers have described Hygiea as a "fairly dusty object", with a regolith layer consisting mostly of fine dust rather than coarse rock.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] This fine regolith has a low thermal inertia, meaning it radiates away heat more easily and leads to cooler temperatures on Hygiea's surface.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The regolith of Hygiea may be dustier (and thus finer) than that of Earth's Moon, which could imply a more mature regolith that has experienced more space weathering.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The regolith layer of Hygiea is estimated to be at least 8 cm (3.1 in) deep.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] These properties of Hygiea's regolith were inferred from the asteroid's lower-than-expected temperature and thermal emission in infrared, submillimetre, and microwave wavelengths.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea is a carbonaceous asteroid whose surface is largely composed of hydrated and ammoniated silicate minerals (phyllosilicates) and carbonates, with hints of water ice.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] This composition is inferred from spectroscopic observations of Hygiea, whose visible and near-infrared spectrum characterize it as a C-type asteroid.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] More broadly, it makes Hygiea a member of the C spectral complex, which is common in the outer main belt where Hygiea resides.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The spectrum and composition of Hygiea's surface is very similar to those of carbonaceous chondrite meteorites and Ceres, which has led some astronomers to call Hygiea a "primitive" object and a "virtual spectral twin of Ceres".
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea's resemblance to carbonaceous chondrites (particularly CM chondrites) suggests it shares a similar history of having undergone little thermal alteration and some aqueous alteration of its original minerals, hence its likely primitive nature.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Slight differences between the near-infrared spectra of Hygiea and Ceres indicate they have slightly different concentrations of hydrated and ammoniated minerals.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] High resolution near-infrared spectroscopy by the James Webb Space Telescope has found that Hygiea's phyllosilicates are magnesium-rich and appear to match ammoniated saponite.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Ground-based observations have shown that the near-infrared spectrum of Hygiea varies over time, which implies there is compositional variation across Hygiea's surface.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] A 2011 study by Vladimir Busarev observed Hygiea's spectral type changing between C, B, and F over the course of its rotation, which he interpreted as an indication of local dehydration of Hygiea's surface material, possibly as a result of heating by impacts.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] A 2019 study by Andrew Rivkin and colleagues reported changes in the 3.1 μm absorption feature in Hygiea's near-infrared spectrum over a time scale of years.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] While this absorption feature is often attributed to ammoniated minerals, its variations could also correspond to either hydrated minerals or potentially water ice frost.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Rivkin and colleagues speculated that the variations could be caused by exposed subsurface material on some parts of Hygiea's surface, although they do not appear to be correlated with one particular surface location.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea's bulk density has been estimated as either 1.944±0.250 g/cm3 or 2.06±0.20 g/cm3, based on measurements of its diameter and mass from 2020 and 2021, respectively.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea's bulk density is similar to that of Ceres (2.16 g/cm3), which together with Hygiea's large size suggests it could have a differentiated interior.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea likely has a water ice-rich subsurface, as hinted by Hygiea's bulk density, spectroscopic detections of water ice, and its lack of large, bowl-shaped craters.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] They further speculated that the higher densities of Hygiea and other large C-type asteroids may be due to a more lithified or compacted interior, as a result of significant aqueous alteration.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Despite its size, Hygiea appears very dim when observed from Earth.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] This is due to its dark surface and its position in the outer main belt.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] For this reason, six smaller asteroids were observed before Annibale de Gasparis discovered Hygiea on 12 April 1849.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Although it is the largest body in its region, due to its dark surface and farther-than-average distance from the Sun, Hygiea appears very dim when observed from Earth.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] In fact, it is the third dimmest of the first twenty-three asteroids discovered, with only 13 Egeria and 17 Thetis having lower mean opposition magnitudes.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] At most oppositions, Hygiea has a magnitude of around +10.2, which is as much as four orders fainter than Vesta, and observation calls for at least a 4-inch (100 mm) telescope to resolve.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] However, at a perihelic opposition, Hygiea can reach +9.1 magnitude and may just be resolvable with 10 × 50 binoculars, unlike the next two largest asteroids in the asteroid belt, 704 Interamnia and 511 Davida, which are always beyond binocular visibility.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] A total of 17 stellar occultations by Hygiea have been tracked by Earth-based astronomers, including two (in 2002 and 2014) that were seen by a large number of observers.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The observations have been used to constrain Hygiea's size, shape and rotation axis.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The Hubble Space Telescope has resolved the asteroid and ruled out the presence of any orbiting companions larger than about 16 kilometres (9.9 mi) in diameter.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea has not been explored by any space probe.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Sykes and others from the Planetary Science Institute proposed the *Exploring the Very Earliest Epoch* (EVE) mission to NASA, as part of the Discovery Program.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The proposal, which did not get approved, suggested launching a copy of the *Dawn* probe to Hygiea in October 2011 and arriving to the asteroid via rendezvous in 2021.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] In 2013, Pierre Vernazza and Philippe Lamy proposed the medium-class mission *INSIDER* for the European Space Agency's Space Programme.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The proposal, which also did not get approved, suggested rendezvousing and orbiting around two or three large main-belt asteroids before releasing one or two landers.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] Hygiea and 24 Themis were among the potential targets of the *INSIDER* mission concept.
[src:comet/10-hygiea] The exploration of primitive main-belt asteroids like Hygiea could provide clues to the processes that led to the formation of the Solar System.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] Hartley 2 was the target of a flyby of the *Deep Impact* spacecraft, as part of the EPOXI mission, on 4 November 2010, which was able to approach within 700 km (430 mi) of Hartley 2 as part of its extended mission.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] As of November 2010 Hartley 2 is the smallest comet which has been visited.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] It is the fifth comet visited by spacecraft, and the second comet visited by the Deep Impact spacecraft, which first visited comet Tempel 1 on 4 July 2005.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] Comet Hartley 2 is a small Jupiter-family comet having an orbital period of 6.46 years.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] It was discovered by Malcolm Hartley in 1986 at the Schmidt Telescope Unit, Siding Spring Observatory, Australia.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] It has the perihelion near the Earth's orbit at 1.05 AU (157 million km) from the Sun.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] The comet passed within 0.12 AU (18 million km) of Earth on 20 October 2010, only eight days before coming to perihelion on 28 October 2010.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] From northern latitudes, during early November 2010, the comet was visible around midnight without interference from the Moon.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] The comet reached an apparent magnitude of about 5 and became dimly visible by naked eye.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] It came to perihelion on 12 October 2023 and brightened to about magnitude 8.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] Despite its current close passage by Earth's orbit, the comet is not yet a known source of meteor showers.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] Dust trails from the recent returns of 103P/Hartley 2 move in and out of Earth's orbit, and the 1979-dust trail is expected to hit in 2062 and 2068.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] Observation by the Spitzer Space Telescope in August 2008 showed the comet nucleus to have a radius of 0.57 ± 0.08 km (0.354 ± 0.050 mi) and a low albedo of 0.028.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] The mass of the comet is estimated to be about 300 megatonnes (3.0×1011 kg).
[src:comet/103p-hartley] Barring a catastrophic breakup or major splitting event, the comet should be able to survive up to another 100 apparitions (~700 years) at its current rate of mass loss.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] Radar observations by the Arecibo Observatory during the comet's 2010 apparition revealed that the nucleus is highly elongated and rotates over an 18-hour period.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] The project manager of the EPOXI mission described its shape as "a cross between a bowling pin and a pickle".
[src:comet/103p-hartley] In 2011 Herschel Space Observatory detected the signature of vaporized water in the comet's coma.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] Hartley 2 contains half as much heavy water as other comets analyzed before, with the same ratio between heavy water and regular water as found in Earth's oceans.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] For many years, it was known that few comets produced more water vapor than it should by the redirection of nucleus of water ice.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] The flyby of Hartley 2 showed that many of the icy grains in the coma are driven out by the outgassing of carbon dioxide.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] It is believed that this is the source of much of the water coming from the comet.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] Observations of Hartley 2 showed the importance of carbon-monoxide ice to carbon-dioxide ice in comets.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] After a reexamination, it was found that the abundances of carbon-monoxide ice and carbon dioxide ice show that short-period comets formed under warmer conditions, than the longer period comets.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] This shows that the short-period comets formed closer to the Sun, than the long-term comets.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] This discovery goes well with the measurements of Heavy Water in Hartley 2.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] The *Deep Impact* spacecraft, which had previously photographed Comet Tempel 1, was reused by NASA to study Hartley 2.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] The initial plan was for a flyby of Comet Boethin.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] However, Boethin had not been observed since 1986, and its orbit could not be calculated with sufficient precision to permit a flyby, so NASA re-targeted the spacecraft toward Hartley 2 instead.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] The data from the flyby were transmitted back to Earth through NASA's Deep Space Network.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] The flyby was able to show that the comet is 2.25 km (1.40 mi) long, and "peanut shaped".
[src:comet/103p-hartley] Some jets of material are being ejected from the dark side of the comet, rather than the sunlit side.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] NASA's scientists reported that the rays coming off the rough ends consist of hundreds of tons of fluffy ice and dust chunks – the largest particles are of golf ball to basketball-size – and they are ejected by jets of carbon dioxide.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] The scientists also said that it was the first time that comet activity powered by sublimation of frozen carbon dioxide had been observed as the comet neared the Sun; the CO2 ice within the comet must be primordial, dating from the beginnings of the Solar System.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] The EPOXI mission flyby showed that the material being ejected from the comet is primarily composed of CO2 gas.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] A University of Maryland-led study published in 17 June issue of the journal *Science* described an analysis of the mission.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] Moreover, these objects appear to be two to three times more reflective than the surface average.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] It is now believed that some of the dust, icy chunks, and other material coming off the ends of the comet are moving slowly enough to be captured by even the weak gravity of the comet.
[src:comet/103p-hartley] This material then falls back into the lowest point—the middle.
[src:comet/108p-ciffréo] The comet was discovered by Jacqueline Ciffréo on 8 November 1985 using a 0.9 m Schmidt camera at Caussols.
[src:comet/108p-ciffréo] The comet was then a diffuse object with an apparent magnitude of 10.
[src:comet/108p-ciffréo] Kosai from the Tokyo Observatory noticed on 9 November that it also had a faint tail about 1.5 arcminutes long.
[src:comet/108p-ciffréo] An elliptical orbit was published by Daniel W.
[src:comet/108p-ciffréo] Green on 18 November, with an estimated orbital period of 7.81 years, while perihelion had taken place on 28 October 1985 at a distance of 1.72 AU (257 million km).
[src:comet/108p-ciffréo] Further observations revealed that the perihelion was on 30 October and the orbital period of the comet was 7.22 years.
[src:comet/108p-ciffréo] In December 1985, a detacted coma or tail was detected 6 arcseconds from the nucleus of the comet and extending for 20 arcseconds to the north-east.
[src:comet/108p-ciffréo] The visual magnitude of the comet was estimated to be 12.5.
[src:comet/108p-ciffréo] The comet was recovered on 24 September 1992 by J.
[src:comet/108p-ciffréo] The comet passed perihelion on 23 January 1993.
[src:comet/108p-ciffréo] The next perihelion was in April 2000 and the comet was observed in November and December 1999 and November and December 2000.
[src:comet/108p-ciffréo] During the 2014 and 2021 apparition the comet featured a detached coma, similar to that observed in 1985.
[src:comet/108p-ciffréo] The peculiar morphology was attributed to a possible fragmentation event, but further observations revealed it is most probably an artifact of the turnaround of particles ejected sunward and repelled by sunlight.
[src:comet/108p-ciffréo] The comet is at a 5:3 orbital resonance with Jupiter, allowing for frequent planetary encounters.
[src:comet/108p-ciffréo] Between 1900 and 2183, its closest approach to Jupiter will occur on 18 December 2076 at a distance of 0.28 AU (42 million km).
[src:comet/108p-ciffréo] Initial orbital calculations of the comet indicated that it was a recently captured object.
[src:comet/108p-ciffréo] However, follow-up studies in 1990 later revealed that its dynamical behavior corresponds to a relatively "aged" object instead, where it has been on its current orbit for at least 1,500 revolutions since at least 12,000 BC.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] As of mid-June 2026, the comet is around apparent magnitude 13 with a declination of –09.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] At the perihelion passage on 2 August 2026 the solar elongation will be 164 degrees at a magnitude of approximately 8–10 with a declination of –24.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] The closest approach to Earth will be the next day on 3 August 2026 at a distance of 0.414 AU (61.9 million km).
[src:comet/10p-tempel] The comet should get into the reach of binoculars.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] The comet nucleus is estimated to be roughly the size of Halley's Comet at 10.6 km (6.6 mi) in diameter with a low albedo of 0.022.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] The nucleus is dark because hydrocarbons on the surface have been converted to a dark, tar like substance by solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] The nucleus is large enough that even near aphelion (furthest distance from the Sun which is near the orbit of Jupiter) the comet remains brighter than about magnitude 21.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] During the 2010 apparition the comet brightened to about apparent magnitude 8.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] The most favorable apparition of 10P/Tempel 2 was in 1925 when it came within 0.35 AU (52 million km; 33 million mi) of Earth with an apparent magnitude of 6.5.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] Photometry during four apparitions between 1983 and 2011 shows that cometary activity increases sharply about three months before perihelion and after perihelion declines steadily and slowly.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] Infrared spectroscopy conducted in July 2010 revealed the presence of CH3OH, C2H6, NH3 and HCN in trace amounts within its coma, with their peak intensities suggesting a possible existence of a distributed source that was released from the nucleus as sublimed icy grains.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] Observations by the Infrared Astronomical Satellite in 1983 showed that the comet has a dust trail.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] At that time it has the most prominent of the observed dust trails and extended for over 48 degrees in the sky while it was narrow, less than 4 arcminutes thick.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] The particles that comprise it have a diameter over one millemeter and were ejected from the comet over a period of hundreds of years with velocities of several meters per second with respect to the comet.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] The particles in front of the comet have a dimater of at least 6 mm.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] Photometry of the comet in 2010-2011 indicated that the nucleus was rotating once every 8.950 ± 0.002 hours.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] That rotational period was higher than that calculated in 1999, when it was 8.941 ± 0.002 hours, which in turn was higher than that in 1988, indicating that the nuclear rotation rate was slowing due to asymmetric outgassing.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] The comet features an almost linear jet in CN and red images by the Lowell Observatory whose appearance changes only slightly during the rotation of the comet, originating from a small region near the pole of the comet.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] The Jet Propulsion Laboratory proposed a flyby of the comet with a flight spare of *Mariner 4*.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] The probe was instead used for a Venus flyby as *Mariner 5*.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] It was the original target of the Comet Rendezvous Asteroid Flyby (CRAF) mission before it was switched to 22P/Kopff due to developmental delays, until its eventual cancellation in 1992.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] 10P/Tempel was to be the target of the NASA part of the International Comet Mission after transporting a European probe to a flyby of Halley's Comet.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] The plan was to use Solar electric propulsion to get the craft to orbit the comet.
[src:comet/10p-tempel] The program was cancelled in November 1979.
[src:comet/113p-spitaler] While attempting to observe C/1890 V1 (Zona), which was just discovered about two days earlier, Rudolf Ferdinand Spitaler spotted a new comet on the night of 17 November 1890.
[src:comet/113p-spitaler] He described it as a very nebulous object positioned very close on where Zona's Comet was predicted to be, albeit fainter than the latter.
[src:comet/113p-spitaler] Both comets were found within the constellation Auriga.
[src:comet/113p-spitaler] It was last detected on 4 February 1891, when Spitaler described it as very faint and diffuse.
[src:comet/113p-spitaler] Spitaler, together with George Mary Searle, James Francis Tennant, and John Russell Hind, calculated orbits based on the observations, but despite predictions of a return in 1897, it was lost and remained so for the next 102 years.
[src:comet/113p-spitaler] Around this time, the comet made two close approaches to Jupiter between 1947 and 1983, at distances of 1.318 AU (197.2 million km) and 0.401 AU (60.0 million km), respectively.
[src:comet/113p-spitaler] On 24 October 1993, the comet was rediscovered by James Vernon Scotti from the Spacewatch survey.
[src:comet/113p-spitaler] It was confirmed as the same object as Spitaler's Comet when Brian G.
[src:comet/113p-spitaler] Marsden calculated its orbit and connected its 1890 and 1994 apparitions.
[src:comet/113p-spitaler] It was then subsequently observed on every apparition up to the present day.
[src:comet/113p-spitaler] Photometric observations of the comet until 2000 revealed that the nucleus of Spitaler's Comet has an effective radius of around 1.15 km (0.71 mi).
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] 2006 VW139 was discovered on 15 November 2006, by the Spacewatch survey at Kitt Peak National Observatory near Tucson, Arizona.
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] The possible cometary activity was seen in November 2011 by Pan-STARRS.
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] Both Spacewatch and Pan-STARRS are asteroid survey projects of NASA's Near Earth Object Observations Program.
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] After the Pan-STARRS observations it was also given a comet designation of 288P.
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] 2006 VW139 is a non-family asteroid of the main-belt's background population.
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] It is both a binary asteroid and a main-belt comet, also known as "active asteroid".
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] It orbits the Sun in the outer main-belt at a distance of 2.4–3.7 AU once every 5 years and 4 months (1,944 days; semi-major axis of 3.05 AU).
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] Its orbit has an eccentricity of 0.20 and an inclination of 3° with respect to the ecliptic.
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] The body's observation arc begins in September 2000, with a precovery taken by the Sloan Digital Sky Survey at Apache Point Observatory, New Mexico, more than six years prior to its official discovery observation by Spacewatch at Kitt Peak.
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] 2006 VW139 was first observed by the Hubble Space Telescope (HST) in December 2011.
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] It was imaged by HST in September 2016, just before it made its closest approach to the Sun and confirmed its binary nature with two asteroids orbiting each other, and revealed ongoing cometary activity.
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] This makes the object the first known binary asteroid that is also classified as a main-belt comet.
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] The binary is thought to be the result of fission of the precursor caused by YORP-driven spinup.
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] Observations of the HST revealed ongoing activity in this binary system.
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] The combined features of this binary asteroid - wide separation, near-equal component size, high eccentricity orbit, and comet-like activity also make it unique among the few known binary asteroids that have a wide separation.
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] 2006 VW139 has a derived diameter of 1.8±0.2 kilometer.
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] The *Collaborative Asteroid Lightcurve Link* assumes an albedo of 0.057 and calculates a diameter of 3.20 kilometers based on an absolute magnitude of 16.2.
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] The binary system has an estimated mass between 1.3×1012 kg and 1.1×1013 kg.
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] A single component has a derived mass of (6.15±4.85)×1012 kg.
[src:comet/300163-2006-vw139] This minor planet was numbered by the Minor Planet Center on 12 October 2011 (M.P.C.
[src:comet/457175-2008-go98] 2008 GO98 is classified as a member of the dynamical Hilda group, as well as a Jupiter family that shows clear cometary activity, which has also been described as a "quasi-Hilda comet".
[src:comet/457175-2008-go98] Orbital backward integration suggests that it might have been a centaur or trans-Neptunian object that ended its dynamical evolution as a quasi-Hilda comet.
[src:comet/457175-2008-go98] It may have reached the belt during the last few hundred years.
[src:comet/457175-2008-go98] It orbits the Sun in the outer asteroid belt at a distance of 2.9–5.1 AU once every 7 years and 11 months (2,883 days; semi-major axis of 3.96 AU).
[src:comet/457175-2008-go98] Its orbit has an eccentricity of 0.28 and an inclination of 16° with respect to the ecliptic.
[src:comet/457175-2008-go98] The body's observation arc begins with a precovery taken by the Sloan Digital Sky Survey in October 2001, more than 5 years prior to its official discovery observation by Spacewatch.
[src:comet/457175-2008-go98] Although 2008 GO98 orbits in the asteroid belt, it has a Jupiter Tisserand's parameter (TJ) of 2.926, just below Jewitt's threshold of 3, which serves as a distinction between the main-belt asteroids (TJ larger than 3) and the Jupiter-family comets (TJ between 2 and 3).
[src:comet/457175-2008-go98] This minor planet was numbered by the Minor Planet Center on 16 February 2016 (M.P.C.
[src:comet/457175-2008-go98] 2008 GO98 is an assumed C-type asteroid.
[src:comet/457175-2008-go98] In August 2017, a rotational lightcurve of 2008 GO98 was obtained from photometric observations by American astronomer Brian Warner at the Palmer Divide Station (U82) in California.
[src:comet/457175-2008-go98] Lightcurve analysis gave a rotation period of 10.74±0.01 hours with a small brightness amplitude of 0.12 magnitude (U=2).
[src:comet/457175-2008-go98] The *Collaborative Asteroid Lightcurve Link* assumes a standard albedo for a carbonaceous body of 0.057 and calculates a diameter of 14.64 kilometers based on an absolute magnitude of 12.9.
[src:comet/457175-2008-go98] Other estimates, taking into account several published magnitude measurements and a large range of albedo assumptions, estimate a diameter range of 5.5 to 24.7 kilometers.
[src:comet/comet-p01] A **comet** is an icy, small Solar System body or interstellar object that warms and begins to release gases when passing close to the Sun, a process called outgassing.
[src:comet/comet-p01] This produces an extended, gravitationally unbound atmosphere or coma surrounding the nucleus, and sometimes a tail of gas and dust gas blown out from the coma.
[src:comet/comet-p01] These phenomena are due to the effects of solar radiation and the outstreaming solar wind plasma acting upon the nucleus of the comet.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Comet nuclei range from a few hundred meters to tens of kilometers across and are composed of loose collections of ice, dust, and small rocky particles.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The coma may be up to 15 times Earth's diameter, while the tail may stretch beyond one astronomical unit.
[src:comet/comet-p01] If sufficiently close and bright, a comet may be seen from Earth without the aid of a telescope and can subtend an arc of up to 30° (60 Moons) across the sky.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Comets have been observed and recorded since ancient times by many cultures and religions.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Comets usually have highly eccentric elliptical orbits, and they have a wide range of orbital periods, ranging from several years to potentially several millions of years.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Short-period comets originate in the Kuiper belt or its associated scattered disc, which lie beyond the orbit of Neptune.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Long-period comets are thought to originate in the Oort cloud, a spherical cloud of icy bodies extending from outside the Kuiper belt to halfway to the nearest star.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Long-period comets are set in motion towards the Sun by gravitational perturbations from passing stars and the galactic tide.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Hyperbolic comets may pass once through the inner Solar System before being flung to interstellar space.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The appearance of a comet is called an apparition.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Comets contain volatile material that sublimate as they approach the Sun to produce the characteristic tail, but asteroids are more like rocks and form no tail.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Asteroids are thought to have a different origin from comets, having formed inside the orbit of Jupiter rather than in the outer Solar System.
[src:comet/comet-p01] However, the discovery of main-belt comets and active centaur minor planets has blurred the distinction between asteroids and comets.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In the early 21st century, the discovery of some minor bodies with long-period comet orbits, but characteristics of inner solar system asteroids, were called Manx comets.
[src:comet/comet-p01] They are still classified as comets, such as C/2014 S3 (PANSTARRS).
[src:comet/comet-p01] Twenty-seven Manx comets were found from 2013 to 2017.
[src:comet/comet-p01] As of November 2021, there are 4,584 known comets.
[src:comet/comet-p01] However, this represents a very small fraction of the total potential comet population, as the reservoir of comet-like bodies in the outer Solar System (in the Oort cloud) is about one trillion.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Roughly one comet per year is visible to the naked eye, though many of those are faint and unspectacular.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Particularly bright examples are called "great comets".
[src:comet/comet-p01] Comets have been visited by uncrewed probes such as NASA's *Deep Impact*, which blasted a crater on Comet Tempel 1 to study its interior, and the European Space Agency's *Rosetta*, which became the first to land a robotic spacecraft on a comet.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The word *comet* derives from the Old English *cometa* from the Latin *comēta* or *comētēs*.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The astronomical symbol for comets (represented in Unicode) is U+2604 ☄ COMET, consisting of a small disc with three hairlike extensions.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The solid, core structure of a comet is known as the nucleus.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Cometary nuclei are composed of an amalgamation of rock, dust, water ice, and frozen carbon dioxide, carbon monoxide, methane, and ammonia.
[src:comet/comet-p01] As such, they are popularly described as "dirty snowballs" after Fred Whipple's model.
[src:comet/comet-p01] However after observation of Comet 9P/Tempel 1 collision with an "impactor" probe sent by NASA Deep Impact mission in July 2005, "icy dirtballs" may be more appropriate.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Research conducted in 2014 suggests that comets are like "deep fried ice cream", in that their surfaces are formed of dense crystalline ice mixed with organic compounds, while the interior ice is colder and less dense.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The surface of the nucleus is generally dry, dusty or rocky, suggesting that the ices are hidden beneath a surface crust several metres thick.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Nuclei contain a variety of organic compounds, which may include methanol, hydrogen cyanide, formaldehyde, ethanol, ethane, and perhaps more complex molecules such as long-chain hydrocarbons and amino acids.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In 2009, it was confirmed that the amino acid glycine had been found in the comet dust recovered by NASA's Stardust mission.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In August 2011, a report, based on NASA studies of meteorites found on Earth, was published suggesting DNA and RNA components (adenine, guanine, and related organic molecules) may have been formed on asteroids and comets.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The outer surfaces of cometary nuclei have a very low albedo, making them among the least reflective objects found in the Solar System.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The Giotto space probe found that the nucleus of Halley's Comet (1P/Halley) reflects about four percent of the light that falls on it, and Deep Space 1 discovered that Comet Borrelly's surface reflects less than 3.0%; by comparison, asphalt reflects seven percent.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The dark surface material of the nucleus may consist of complex organic compounds.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Solar heating drives off lighter volatile compounds, leaving behind larger organic compounds that tend to be very dark, like tar or crude oil.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The low reflectivity of cometary surfaces causes them to absorb the heat that drives their outgassing processes.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Comet nuclei with radii of up to 30 kilometers (19 mi) have been observed, but ascertaining their exact size is difficult.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The nucleus of 322P/SOHO is probably only 100–200 meters (330–660 ft) in diameter.
[src:comet/comet-p01] A lack of smaller comets being detected despite the increased sensitivity of instruments has led some to suggest that there is a real lack of comets smaller than 100 meters (330 ft) across.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Known comets have been estimated to have an average density of 0.6 g/cm3 (0.35 oz/cu in).
[src:comet/comet-p01] Because of their low mass, comet nuclei do not become spherical under their own gravity and therefore have irregular shapes.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Results from the *Rosetta* and *Philae* spacecraft show that the nucleus of 67P/Churyumov–Gerasimenko has no magnetic field, which suggests that magnetism may not have played a role in the early formation of planetesimals.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Instruments on the *Philae* lander found at least sixteen organic compounds at the comet's surface, four of which (acetamide, acetone, methyl isocyanate and propionaldehyde) have been detected for the first time on a comet.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The streams of dust and gas thus released form a huge and extremely thin atmosphere around the comet called the "coma".
[src:comet/comet-p01] The force exerted on the coma by the Sun's radiation pressure and solar wind cause an enormous "tail" to form pointing away from the Sun.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The coma is generally made of water and dust, with water making up to 90% of the volatiles that outflow from the nucleus when the comet is within 3 to 4 AU (450 to 600 million km; 280 to 370 million mi) of the Sun.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The H2O parent molecule is destroyed primarily through photodissociation and to a much lesser extent photoionization, with the solar wind playing a minor role in the destruction of water compared to photochemistry.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Larger dust particles are left along the comet's orbital path whereas er particles are pushed away from the Sun into the comet's tail by light pressure.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Although the solid nucleus of comets is generally less than 60 kilometers (37 mi) across, the coma may be thousands or millions of kilometers across.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Occasionally a comet may experience a huge and sudden outburst of gas and dust, during which the size of the coma greatly increases for a period of time.
[src:comet/comet-p01] For example, about a month after an outburst in October 2007, comet 17P/Holmes briefly had a tenuous dust atmosphere larger than the Sun.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The Great Comet of 1811 had a coma roughly the diameter of the Sun.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Even though the coma can become quite large, its size can decrease about the time it crosses the orbit of Mars around 1.5 AU (220 million km; 140 million mi) from the Sun.
[src:comet/comet-p01] At this distance the solar wind becomes strong enough to blow the gas and dust away from the coma, and in doing so enlarging the tail.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In 1996, comets were found to emit X-rays.
[src:comet/comet-p01] This greatly surprised astronomers because X-ray emission is usually associated with very high-temperature bodies.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Cravens was the first to propose an explanation in early 1997.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The X-rays are generated by the interaction between comets and the solar wind: when highly charged solar wind ions fly through a cometary atmosphere, they collide with cometary atoms and molecules, "stealing" one or more electrons from the atom in a process called "charge exchange".
[src:comet/comet-p01] This exchange or transfer of an electron to the solar wind ion is followed by its de-excitation into the ground state of the ion by the emission of X-rays and far ultraviolet photons.
[src:comet/comet-p01] As a comet approaches the Sun, UV light ionizes gases in the coma.
[src:comet/comet-p01] When the solar wind interacts with these ionized particles, mainly OH and CO group molecules, the solar wind plasma is decelerated in a large region around the comet: a cometary-mode bow shock forms.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The cometary bow shock resembles the classical bow shock observed when a planetary magnetic field, like that around Earth, Jupiter, Saturn, or Neptune, interacts with the solar wind.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Like Mars and Venus, comets are said to have an induced magnetosphere.
[src:comet/comet-p01] A comet may have a dust tail, an ion tail, both or neither.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The dust and ion tails both begin when sunlight vaporizes material from the comet.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The dust tail contains particle about the size of human hairs.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Radiation pressure from the Sun pushes these dust particles away, resulting in a gentle arc shape.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Larger particles, the size of pebbles, are pulled towards the Sun, staying on the orbit of the comet.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The ion tail contains molecule sized particles ionized by the Sun then captured by the magnetic field created by the interaction between these ions and the solar wind.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The ion tail points directly away from the Sun following magnetic field lines.
[src:comet/comet-p01] On occasions—such as when Earth passes through a comet's orbital plane, the antitail, pointing in the opposite direction to the ion and dust tails, may be seen.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Uneven heating can cause newly generated gases to break out of a weak spot on the surface of comet's nucleus, like a geyser.
[src:comet/comet-p01] These streams of gas and dust can cause the nucleus to spin, and even split apart.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In 2010 it was revealed that sublimation of dry ice (frozen carbon dioxide) can power jets of material flowing out of a comet nucleus.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Infrared imaging of Hartley 2 shows such jets exiting and carrying with it dust grains into the coma.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Most comets are small Solar System bodies with elongated elliptical orbits that take them close to the Sun for a part of their orbit and then out into the further reaches of the Solar System for the remainder.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Technically, these objects have a perihelion, their nearest point to the Sun of less that 4 AU, that is controlled by the gravity of Jupiter and not controlled by the gravity of another planet near the perihelion.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Comets can be subdivided according to their aphelion distance, how far away from the Sun they can orbit.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The four subdivisions, E for Encke, SP for short-period, I for intermediate, and L for long-period, have names derived from an earlier classification based on the length of their orbital periods.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Single-apparition or non-periodic comets have parabolic or hyperbolic trajectories.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The low mass and elliptical orbits cause comet orbits to be altered by gravitational forces from giant planets and these single-apparition comets orbit the Sun one time then permanently exit the Solar System.
[src:comet/comet-p01] At the shorter orbital period extreme, Encke's Comet has an orbit that does not reach the orbit of Jupiter, and is known as an **Encke-type comet**.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Short-period comets with orbital periods less than 20 years and low inclinations (up to 30 degrees) to the ecliptic are called traditional **Jupiter-family comets** (JFCs).
[src:comet/comet-p01] Those like Halley, with orbital periods of between 20 and 200 years and inclinations extending from zero to more than 90 degrees, are called **Halley-type comets** (HTCs).
[src:comet/comet-p01] As of July 2025 there are 74 known Encke-type comets (six of which are classified as near-Earth objects (NEOs)), 109 HTCs (36 of which are NEOs), and 815 JFCs (153 of which are NEOs).
[src:comet/comet-p01] Recently discovered main-belt comets form a distinct class, orbiting in more circular orbits within the asteroid belt.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Periodic comets or short-period comets are generally defined as those having orbital periods of less than 200 years.
[src:comet/comet-p01] They usually orbit more-or-less in the ecliptic plane in the same direction as the planets.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Their orbits typically take them out to the region of the outer planets (Jupiter and beyond) at aphelion; for example, the aphelion of Halley's Comet is a little beyond the orbit of Neptune.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Comets whose aphelia are near a major planet's orbit are called its "family".
[src:comet/comet-p01] Such families are thought to arise from the planet capturing formerly long-period comets into shorter orbits.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Because their elliptical orbits frequently take them close to the giant planets, comets are subject to further gravitational perturbations.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Short-period comets have a tendency for their aphelia to coincide with a giant planet's semi-major axis, with the JFCs being the largest group.
[src:comet/comet-p01] It is clear that comets coming in from the Oort cloud often have their orbits strongly influenced by the gravity of giant planets as a result of a close encounter.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Jupiter is the source of the greatest perturbations, being more than twice as massive as all the other planets combined.
[src:comet/comet-p01] These perturbations can deflect long-period comets into shorter orbital periods.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Vast swarms of comet-like bodies are thought to orbit the Sun in these distant regions in roughly circular orbits.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Occasionally the gravitational influence of the outer planets (in the case of Kuiper belt objects) or nearby stars (in the case of Oort cloud objects) may throw one of these bodies into an elliptical orbit that takes it inwards toward the Sun to form a visible comet.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Unlike the return of periodic comets, whose orbits have been established by previous observations, the appearance of new comets by this mechanism is unpredictable.
[src:comet/comet-p01] When flung into the orbit of the sun, and being continuously dragged towards it, tons of matter are stripped from the comets which greatly influence their lifetime; the more stripped, the shorter they live and vice versa.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Comets with periods greater than 30 years but less than 200 years have been called intermediate period comets, but other definitions have been used.
[src:comet/comet-p01] They can be considered to have aphelion 35–1000 AU.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Long-period comets have highly eccentric orbits and periods ranging from 200 years to thousands or even millions of years.
[src:comet/comet-p01] They have aphelion greater than 1000 AU.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Less than a dozen of such comets are observed annually, but studying them is important as a way to learn more about the Oort cloud where they primarily originate.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Jan Oort himself discovered the key facts about these comets including their nearly parabolic orbits oriented randomly around the Sun.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Subsequent studies showed that galactic tides and the gravitational push of passing stars are sufficient to create a comet from objects in the Oort cloud.
[src:comet/comet-p01] About half of these comets are ejected from the Solar System on their first pass by the Sun due to the gravity of the planets.
[src:comet/comet-p01] As long-period comets approach the Sun their orbital eccentricity oscillates in sync with the orbit of Jupiter and falls as the comet passes the orbit of Uranus.
[src:comet/comet-p01] As of 2025, three objects have been discovered with an eccentricity significantly greater than one: 1I/ʻOumuamua, 2I/Borisov, and 3I/ATLAS, indicating an origin outside the Solar System.
[src:comet/comet-p01] While ʻOumuamua, with an eccentricity of about 1.2, showed no optical signs of cometary activity during its passage through the inner Solar System in October 2017, changes to its trajectory—which suggests outgassing—indicate that it is probably a comet.
[src:comet/comet-p01] On the other hand, 2I/Borisov, with an estimated eccentricity of about 3.36, has been observed to have the coma feature of comets, and is considered the first detected interstellar comet.
[src:comet/comet-p01] 3I/ATLAS has an eccentricity of about 6.1, and also has a coma, indicating that it is also a comet.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Comet C/1980 E1 had an orbital period of roughly 7.1 million years before the 1982 perihelion passage, but a 1980 encounter with Jupiter accelerated the comet giving it the largest eccentricity (1.057) of any known solar comet with a reasonable observation arc.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Early observations have revealed a few genuinely hyperbolic (i.e. non-periodic) trajectories, but no more than could be accounted for by perturbations from Jupiter.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Comets from interstellar space are moving with velocities of the same order as the relative velocities of stars near the Sun (a few tens of km per second).
[src:comet/comet-p01] When such objects enter the Solar System, they have a positive specific orbital energy resulting in a positive velocity at infinity ( $v_{\infty }\!$ ) and have notably hyperbolic trajectories.
[src:comet/comet-p01] A rough calculation shows that there might be four hyperbolic comets per century within Jupiter's orbit, give or take one and perhaps two orders of magnitude.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Exocomets beyond the Solar System have been detected and may be common in the Milky Way.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The first exocomet system detected was around Beta Pictoris, a very young A-type main-sequence star, in 1987.
[src:comet/comet-p01] A total of 11 such exocomet systems have been identified as of 2013, using the absorption spectrum caused by the large clouds of gas emitted by comets when passing close to their star.
[src:comet/comet-p01] For ten years the Kepler space telescope was responsible for searching for planets and other forms outside of the solar system.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The first transiting exocomets were found in February 2018 by a group consisting of professional astronomers and citizen scientists in light curves recorded by the Kepler Space Telescope.
[src:comet/comet-p01] After Kepler Space Telescope retired in October 2018, a new telescope called TESS Telescope has taken over Kepler's mission.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Since the launch of TESS, astronomers have discovered the transits of comets around the star Beta Pictoris using a light curve from TESS.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Since TESS has taken over, astronomers have since been able to better distinguish exocomets with the spectroscopic method.
[src:comet/comet-p01] New planets are detected by the white light curve method which is viewed as a symmetrical dip in the charts readings when a planet overshadows its parent star.
[src:comet/comet-p01] However, after further evaluation of these light curves, it has been discovered that the asymmetrical patterns of the dips presented are caused by the tail of a comet or of hundreds of comets.
[src:comet/comet-p01] As a comet is heated during close passes to the Sun, outgassing of its icy components releases solid debris too large to be swept away by radiation pressure and the solar wind.
[src:comet/comet-p01] If Earth's orbit sends it through that trail of debris, which is composed mostly of fine grains of rocky material, there is likely to be a meteor shower as Earth passes through.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Denser trails of debris produce quick but intense meteor showers and less dense trails create longer but less intense showers.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Typically, the density of the debris trail is related to how long ago the parent comet released the material.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The Perseid meteor shower, for example, occurs every year between 9 and 13 August, when Earth passes through the orbit of Comet Swift–Tuttle.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Halley's Comet is the source of the Orionid shower in October.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Many comets and asteroids collided with Earth in its early stages.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Many scientists think that comets bombarding the young Earth about 4 billion years ago brought the vast quantities of water that now fill Earth's oceans, or at least a significant portion of it.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The detection of organic molecules, including polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, in significant quantities in comets has led to speculation that comets or meteorites may have brought the precursors of life—or even life itself—to Earth.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In 2013 it was suggested that impacts between rocky and icy surfaces, such as comets, had the potential to create the amino acids that make up proteins through shock synthesis.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The speed at which the comets entered the atmosphere, combined with the magnitude of energy created after initial contact, allowed smaller molecules to condense into the larger macro-molecules that served as the foundation for life.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In 2015, scientists found significant amounts of molecular oxygen in the outgassings of comet 67P, suggesting that the molecule may occur more often than had been thought, and thus less an indicator of life as has been supposed.
[src:comet/comet-p01] It is suspected that comet impacts have, over long timescales, delivered significant quantities of water to Earth's Moon, some of which may have survived as lunar ice.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Comet and meteoroid impacts are thought to be responsible for the existence of tektites and australites.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Fear of comets as acts of God and signs of impending doom was highest in Europe from 1200 to 1650 CE.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The year after the Great Comet of 1618, for example, Gotthard Arthusius published a pamphlet stating that it was a sign that the Day of Judgment was near.
[src:comet/comet-p01] He listed ten pages of comet-related disasters, including "earthquakes, floods, changes in river courses, hail storms, hot and dry weather, poor harvests, epidemics, war and treason and high prices".
[src:comet/comet-p01] By 1700 most scholars concluded that such events occurred whether a comet was seen or not.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Using Edmond Halley's records of comet sightings, however, William Whiston in 1711 wrote that the Great Comet of 1680 had a periodicity of 574 years and was responsible for the worldwide flood in the Book of Genesis, by pouring water on Earth.
[src:comet/comet-p01] His announcement revived for another century fear of comets, now as direct threats to the world instead of signs of disasters.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Spectroscopic analysis in 1910 found the toxic gas cyanogen in the tail of Halley's Comet, causing panicked buying of gas masks and quack "anti-comet pills" and "anti-comet umbrellas" by the public.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Comets are believed to represent condensed material from the Solar Nebula, the gas cloud that also lead to the formation of the planets.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Two models have been proposed to explain how micron sized dust and ice aggregates to form the nuclei of a comet.
[src:comet/comet-p01] One model expects pairs of small particles to stick together upon collision, growing larger each time.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Models of this process work up to about one meter, but comet nuclei are much larger.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The second model starts the same way, but at 1 cm, the size of pebbles, the model proposes that hydrodynamic streaming organizes the pebbles as the coalesce gravitationally.
[src:comet/comet-p01] This model is unable to explain how the ball of pebbles can remain cold and fragmentary under internal heat from radionuclide decay and pressure from gravity.
[src:comet/comet-p01] As the small particles grew, the Solar Nebula evolved and dispersed as the orbits of giant planets changed.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The dispersal lead to groups of objects in the Kuiper belt, the Scattered disk, the Oort cloud, as well as objects called Trojans trapped around Jupiter and Neptune.
[src:comet/comet-p01] These distant regions act as cold storage: 40 K for the Kuiper belt and Scattered disk around 35–100 AU, 10 K for the Oort cloud out beyond 3×103 AU.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Active, visible comets are on unstable orbits: they last a few hundred thousand years.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Inactive comets orbit far from the Sun in several different named areas.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The Oort cloud is thought to occupy a vast space starting from between 2,000 and 5,000 AU (0.03 and 0.08 ly). to as far as 50,000 AU (0.79 ly) from the Sun.
[src:comet/comet-p01] This cloud encases the celestial bodies that start at the middle of the Solar System—the Sun, all the way to outer limits of the Kuiper Belt.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The Oort cloud consists of viable materials necessary for the creation of celestial bodies.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The Solar System's planets exist only because of the planetesimals (chunks of leftover space that assisted in the creation of planets) that were condensed and formed by the gravity of the Sun.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The eccentric made from these trapped planetesimals is why the Oort Cloud even exists.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The outer cloud is only weakly bound to the Sun and supplies the long-period (and possibly Halley-type) comets that fall to inside the orbit of Neptune.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The inner Oort cloud is also known as the Hills cloud, named after Jack G.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Hills, who proposed its existence in 1981.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Models predict that the inner cloud should have tens or hundreds of times as many cometary nuclei as the outer halo; it is seen as a possible source of new comets that resupply the relatively tenuous outer cloud as the latter's numbers are gradually depleted.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Closer towards the Sun, the Kuiper Belt is another reservoir of inactive comets.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The most common fate for a comet is ejection from the solar system, followed by random disintegration, tidal disruptions, loss of volatiles on the surface, and collision with large bodies in the Solar System.
[src:comet/comet-p01] If a comet is traveling fast enough, it may leave the Solar System.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Such comets follow the open path of a hyperbola, and as such, they are called hyperbolic comets.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Solar comets are only known to be ejected by interacting with another object in the Solar System, such as Jupiter.
[src:comet/comet-p01] An example of this is Comet C/1980 E1, which was shifted from an orbit of 7.1 million years around the Sun, to a hyperbolic trajectory, after a 1980 close pass by the planet Jupiter.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Interstellar comets such as 1I/ʻOumuamua, 2I/Borisov and 3I/ATLAS never orbited the Sun and therefore do not require a 3rd-body interaction to be ejected from the Solar System.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Dormant or extinct comets have lost their volatile surface material.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Eventually most of the volatile material contained in a comet nucleus evaporates, and the comet becomes a small, dark, inert lump of rock or rubble that can resemble an asteroid.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Since comet orbits are stable longer than the time scale for the comet to lose material, many such extinct comets are expected to exist in the Solar system.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Jupiter-family comets and long-period comets appear to follow very different fading laws.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The JFCs are active over a lifetime of about 10,000 years or ~1,000 orbits whereas long-period comets fade much faster.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Only 10% of the long-period comets survive more than 50 passages to small perihelion and only 1% of them survive more than 2,000 passages.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Some asteroids in elliptical orbits are now identified as extinct comets.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Roughly six percent of the near-Earth asteroids are thought to be extinct comet nuclei.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The nucleus of some comets may be fragile, a conclusion supported by the observation of comets splitting apart.
[src:comet/comet-p01] A significant cometary disruption was that of Comet Shoemaker–Levy 9, which was discovered in 1993.
[src:comet/comet-p01] A close encounter in July 1992 had broken it into pieces, and over a period of six days in July 1994, these pieces fell into Jupiter's atmosphere—the first time astronomers had observed a collision between two objects in the Solar System.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Other splitting comets include 3D/Biela in 1846 and 73P/Schwassmann–Wachmann from 1995 to 2006.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Greek historian Ephorus reported that a comet split apart as far back as the winter of 372–373 BCE.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Comets are suspected of splitting due to thermal stress, internal gas pressure, or impact.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Comets 42P/Neujmin and 53P/Van Biesbroeck appear to be fragments of a parent comet.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Numerical integrations have shown that both comets had a rather close approach to Jupiter in January 1850, and that, before 1850, the two orbits were nearly identical.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Another group of comets that is the result of fragmentation episodes is the Liller comet family made of C/1988 A1 (Liller), C/1996 Q1 (Tabur), C/2015 F3 (SWAN), C/2019 Y1 (ATLAS), and C/2023 V5 (Leonard).
[src:comet/comet-p01] Some comets have been observed to break up during their perihelion passage, including great comets West and Ikeya–Seki.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Biela's Comet was one significant example when it broke into two pieces during its passage through the perihelion in 1846.
[src:comet/comet-p01] These two comets were seen separately in 1852, but never again afterward.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Instead, spectacular meteor showers were seen in 1872 and 1885 when the comet should have been visible.
[src:comet/comet-p01] A minor meteor shower, the Andromedids, occurs annually in November, and it is caused when Earth crosses the orbit of Biela's Comet.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Some comets meet a more spectacular end – either falling into the Sun or colliding with a planet or other body.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Collisions between comets and planets or moons were common in the early Solar System: some of the many craters on the Moon, for example, may have been caused by comets.
[src:comet/comet-p01] A recent collision of a comet with a planet occurred in July 1994 when Comet Shoemaker–Levy 9 broke up into pieces and collided with Jupiter.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The first comet to be associated with an astronomer was Halley's Comet.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Edmond Halley demonstrated that the comets of 1531, 1607, and 1682 were the same body and successfully predicted its return in 1759 by calculating its orbit.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Similarly, the second and third known periodic comets, Encke's Comet and Biela's Comet, were named after the astronomers who calculated their orbits rather than their original discoverers.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Later, periodic comets were usually named after their discoverers, but comets that had appeared only once continued to be referred to by the year of their appearance.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In 1995 a scheme for naming comets based on the minor planet designations was adopted by the International Astronomical Union.
[src:comet/comet-p01] This scheme uses letters, for example *C/* for single-apparition comets or *P/* for periodic comets, followed by the year and a particularly formatted date.
[src:comet/comet-p01] For example, in 2019, astronomer Gennadiy Borisov observed a comet that appeared to have originated outside of the solar system; the comet was named 2I/Borisov after him.
[src:comet/comet-p01] From ancient sources, such as Chinese oracle bones, it is known that comets have been noticed by humans for millennia.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Until the sixteenth century, comets were usually considered bad omens of deaths of kings or noble men, or coming catastrophes, or even interpreted as attacks by heavenly beings against terrestrial inhabitants.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Aristotle (384–322 BCE) was the first known scientist to use various theories and observational facts to employ a consistent, structured cosmological theory of comets.
[src:comet/comet-p01] He believed that comets were atmospheric phenomena, due to the fact that they could appear outside of the zodiac and vary in brightness over the course of a few days.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Aristotle's cometary theory arose from his observations and cosmological theory that everything in the cosmos is arranged in a distinct configuration.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Part of this configuration was a clear separation between the celestial and terrestrial, believing comets to be strictly associated with the latter.
[src:comet/comet-p01] According to Aristotle, comets must be within the sphere of the moon and clearly separated from the heavens.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Also in the 4th century BCE, Apollonius of Myndus supported the idea that comets moved like the planets.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Aristotelian theory on comets continued to be widely accepted throughout the Middle Ages, despite several discoveries from various individuals challenging aspects of it.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In the 1st century CE, Seneca the Younger questioned Aristotle's logic concerning comets.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Because of their regular movement and imperviousness to wind, they cannot be atmospheric, and are more permanent than suggested by their brief flashes across the sky.
[src:comet/comet-p01] He pointed out that only the tails are transparent and thus cloudlike, and argued that there is no reason to confine their orbits to the zodiac.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In the 1st century CE, Pliny the Elder believed that comets were connected with political unrest and death.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Pliny observed comets as "human like", often describing their tails with "long hair" or "long beard".
[src:comet/comet-p01] His system for classifying comets according to their color and shape was used for centuries.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In India, by the 6th century CE astronomers believed that comets were apparitions that re-appeared periodically.
[src:comet/comet-p01] This was the view expressed in the 6th century by the astronomers Varāhamihira and Bhadrabahu, and the 10th-century astronomer Bhaṭṭotpala listed the names and estimated periods of certain comets, but it is not known how these figures were calculated or how accurate they were.
[src:comet/comet-p01] There is a claim that an Arab scholar in 1258 noted several recurrent appearances of a comet (or a type of comet), and though it's not clear if he considered it to be a single periodic comet, it might have been a comet with a period of around 63 years.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In 1301, the Italian painter Giotto was the first person to accurately and anatomically portray a comet.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In his work *Adoration of the Magi,* Giotto's depiction of Halley's Comet in the place of the Star of Bethlehem would go unmatched in accuracy until the 19th century and be bested only with the invention of photography.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Astrological interpretations of comets proceeded to take precedence clear into the 15th century, despite the presence of modern scientific astronomy beginning to take root.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Comets continued to forewarn of disaster, as seen in the *Luzerner Schilling* chronicles and in the warnings of Pope Callixtus III.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In 1578, German Lutheran bishop Andreas Celichius defined comets as "the thick smoke of human sins ... kindled by the hot and fiery anger of the Supreme Heavenly Judge".
[src:comet/comet-p01] Crude attempts at a parallax measurement of Halley's Comet were made in 1456, but were erroneous.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Regiomontanus was the first to attempt to calculate diurnal parallax by observing the Great Comet of 1472.
[src:comet/comet-p01] His predictions were not very accurate, but they were conducted in the hopes of estimating the distance of a comet from Earth.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In the 16th century, Tycho Brahe and Michael Maestlin demonstrated that comets must exist outside of Earth's atmosphere by measuring the parallax of the Great Comet of 1577.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Within the precision of the measurements, this implied the comet must be at least four times more distant than from Earth to the Moon.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Based on observations in 1664, Giovanni Borelli recorded the longitudes and latitudes of comets that he observed, and suggested that cometary orbits may be parabolic.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Despite being a skilled astronomer, in his 1623 book *The Assayer*, Galileo Galilei rejected Brahe's theories on the parallax of comets and claimed that they may be a mere optical illusion, despite little personal observation.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In 1625, Maestlin's student Johannes Kepler upheld that Brahe's view of cometary parallax was correct.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Mathematician Jacob Bernoulli published a treatise on comets in 1682, suggesting comets orbited a point outside the orbit of Saturn, in the manner of epicyles.
[src:comet/comet-p01] During the early modern period comets were studied for their astrological significance in medical disciplines.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Many healers of this time considered medicine and astronomy to be inter-disciplinary and employed their knowledge of comets and other astrological signs for diagnosing and treating patients.
[src:comet/comet-p01] He describes comets as compact and durable solid bodies moving in oblique orbit and their tails as thin streams of vapor emitted by their nuclei, ignited or heated by the Sun.
[src:comet/comet-p01] He suspected that comets were the origin of the life-supporting component of air.
[src:comet/comet-p01] He pointed out that comets usually appear near the Sun, and therefore most likely orbit it.
[src:comet/comet-p01] On their luminosity, he stated, "The comets shine by the Sun's light, which they reflect," with their tails illuminated by "the Sun's light reflected by a smoke arising from [the coma]".
[src:comet/comet-p01] In 1705, Edmond Halley (1656–1742) applied Newton's method to 23 cometary apparitions that had occurred between 1337 and 1698.
[src:comet/comet-p01] He noted that three of these, the comets of 1531, 1607, and 1682, had very similar orbital elements, and he was further able to account for the slight differences in their orbits in terms of gravitational perturbation caused by Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Confident that these three apparitions had been three appearances of the same comet, he predicted that it would appear again in 1758–59.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Halley's predicted return date was later refined by a team of three French mathematicians: Alexis Clairaut, Joseph Lalande, and Nicole-Reine Lepaute, who predicted the date of the comet's 1759 perihelion to within one month's accuracy.
[src:comet/comet-p01] When the comet returned as predicted, it became known as Halley's Comet.
[src:comet/comet-p01] As early as the 18th century, some scientists had made correct hypotheses as to comets' physical composition.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In 1755, Immanuel Kant hypothesized in his *Universal Natural History* that comets were condensed from "primitive matter" beyond the known planets, which is "feebly moved" by gravity, then orbit at arbitrary inclinations, and are partially vaporized by the Sun's heat as they near perihelion.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In the 19th century, the Astronomical Observatory of Padova was an epicenter in the observational study of comets.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Led by Giovanni Santini (1787–1877) and followed by Giuseppe Lorenzoni (1843–1914), this observatory was devoted to classical astronomy, mainly to the new comets and planets orbit calculation, with the goal of compiling a catalog of almost ten thousand stars.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Situated in the Northern portion of Italy, observations from this observatory were key in establishing important geodetic, geographic, and astronomical calculations, such as the difference of longitude between Milan and Padua as well as Padua to Fiume.
[src:comet/comet-p01] Correspondence within the observatory, particularly between Santini and another astronomer Giuseppe Toaldo, mentioned the importance of comet and planetary orbital observations.
[src:comet/comet-p01] In 1950, Fred Lawrence Whipple proposed that rather than being rocky objects containing some ice, comets were icy objects containing some dust and rock.
[src:comet/comet-p01] On 22 January 2014, ESA scientists reported the detection, for the first definitive time, of water vapor on the dwarf planet Ceres, the largest object in the asteroid belt.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The detection was made by using the far-infrared abilities of the Herschel Space Observatory.
[src:comet/comet-p01] The finding is unexpected because comets, not asteroids, are typically considered to "sprout jets and plumes".
[src:comet/comet-p02] Comets can be classified by astronomers using the planets that control their perihelion and aphelion, Tisserand orbital parameters.
[src:comet/comet-p02] Other more qualitative and casual classifications are also possible.
[src:comet/comet-p02] Approximately once a decade, a comet becomes bright enough to be noticed by a casual observer, leading such comets to be designated as great comets.
[src:comet/comet-p02] Predicting whether a comet will become a great comet is notoriously difficult, as many factors may cause a comet's brightness to depart drastically from predictions.
[src:comet/comet-p02] Broadly speaking, if a comet has a large and active nucleus, will pass close to the Sun, and is not obscured by the Sun as seen from Earth when at its brightest, it has a chance of becoming a great comet.
[src:comet/comet-p02] However, Comet Kohoutek in 1973 fulfilled all the criteria and was expected to become spectacular but failed to do so.
[src:comet/comet-p02] Comet West, which appeared three years later, had much lower expectations but became an extremely impressive comet.
[src:comet/comet-p02] The Great Comet of 1577 is a well-known example of a great comet.
[src:comet/comet-p02] It passed near Earth as a non-periodic comet and was seen by many, including well-known astronomers Tycho Brahe and Taqi ad-Din.
[src:comet/comet-p02] Observations of this comet, together with the nova of 1572, cast doubt on the Aristotelian view of a constant universe.
[src:comet/comet-p02] The late 20th century saw a lengthy gap without the appearance of any great comets, followed by the arrival of two in quick succession—Comet Hyakutake in 1996, followed by Hale–Bopp, which reached maximum brightness in 1997 having been discovered two years earlier.
[src:comet/comet-p02] The first great comet of the 21st century was C/2006 P1 (McNaught), which became visible to naked eye observers in January 2007.
[src:comet/comet-p02] A sungrazing comet is a comet that passes extremely close to the Sun at perihelion, generally within a few million kilometers.
[src:comet/comet-p02] Although small sungrazers can be completely evaporated during such a close approach to the Sun, larger sungrazers can survive many perihelion passages.
[src:comet/comet-p02] However, the strong tidal forces they experience often lead to their fragmentation.
[src:comet/comet-p02] About 90% of the sungrazers observed with SOHO are members of the Kreutz group, which all originate from one giant comet that broke up into many smaller comets during its first passage through the inner Solar System.
[src:comet/comet-p02] The remainder contains some sporadic sungrazers, but four other related groups of comets have been identified among them: the Kracht, Kracht 2a, Marsden, and Meyer groups.
[src:comet/comet-p02] The Marsden and Kracht groups both appear to be related to Comet 96P/Machholz, which is the parent of two meteor streams, the Quadrantids and the Arietids.
[src:comet/comet-p02] Of the thousands of known comets, some exhibit unusual properties.
[src:comet/comet-p02] Comet Encke (2P/Encke) orbits from outside the asteroid belt to just inside the orbit of the planet Mercury whereas the Comet 29P/Schwassmann–Wachmann currently travels in a nearly circular orbit entirely between the orbits of Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:comet/comet-p02] 2060 Chiron, whose unstable orbit is between Saturn and Uranus, was originally classified as an asteroid until a faint coma was noticed.
[src:comet/comet-p02] Similarly, Comet Shoemaker–Levy 2 was originally designated asteroid 1990 UL3.
[src:comet/comet-p02] Centaurs typically behave with characteristics of both asteroids and comets.
[src:comet/comet-p02] Centaurs can be classified as comets such as 60558 Echeclus, and 166P/NEAT.
[src:comet/comet-p02] 166P/NEAT was discovered while it exhibited a coma, and so is classified as a comet despite its orbit, and 60558 Echeclus was discovered without a coma but later became active, and was then classified as both a comet and an asteroid (174P/Echeclus).
[src:comet/comet-p02] One plan for *Cassini* involved sending it to a centaur, but NASA decided to destroy it instead.
[src:comet/comet-p02] In the outer Solar System, comets remain frozen and inactive and are extremely difficult or impossible to detect from Earth due to their small size.
[src:comet/comet-p02] Statistical detections of inactive comet nuclei in the Kuiper belt have been reported from observations by the Hubble Space Telescope but these detections have been questioned.
[src:comet/comet-p02] Most comets are too faint to be visible without the aid of a telescope, but a few each decade become bright enough to be visible to the naked eye.
[src:comet/comet-p02] A comet may be discovered photographically using a wide-field telescope or visually with binoculars.
[src:comet/comet-p02] However, even without access to optical equipment, it is still possible for the amateur astronomer to discover a sungrazing comet online by downloading images accumulated by some satellite observatories such as SOHO.
[src:comet/comet-p02] SOHO's 2000th comet was discovered by Polish amateur astronomer Michał Kusiak on 26 December 2010 and both discoverers of Hale–Bopp used amateur equipment (although Hale was not an amateur).
[src:comet/comet-p02] Comets are named by the Minor Planet Center of the International Astronomical Union.
[src:comet/comet-p02] The names start with a prefix related to the object's orbit: P/ for a period of 200 years or less, C/ otherwise, with X/ for unknown and D/ for a periodic comet that has disappeared.
[src:comet/comet-p02] Following the prefix is the date of discovery as a numerical year, uppercase letter for the half-month.
[src:comet/comet-p02] Additional information encoded in the name includes observation of returns.
[src:comet/comet-p02] The depiction of comets in popular culture is firmly rooted in the long Western tradition of seeing comets as harbingers of doom and as omens of world-altering change.
[src:comet/comet-p02] Halley's Comet alone has caused a slew of sensationalist publications of all sorts at each of its reappearances.
[src:comet/comet-p02] In times past, bright comets often inspired panic and hysteria in the general population, being thought of as bad omens.
[src:comet/comet-p02] More recently, during the passage of Halley's Comet in 1910, Earth passed through the comet's tail, and erroneous newspaper reports inspired a fear that cyanogen in the tail might poison millions, whereas the appearance of Comet Hale–Bopp in 1997 triggered the mass suicide of the Heaven's Gate cult.
[src:comet/comet-p02] In science fiction, the impact of comets has been depicted as a threat overcome by technology and heroism (as in the 1998 films *Deep Impact* and *Armageddon*), or as a trigger of global apocalypse (*Lucifer's Hammer*, 1979) or zombies (*Night of the Comet*, 1984).
[src:comet/comet-p02] In Jules Verne's *Off on a Comet* a group of people are stranded on a comet orbiting the Sun, while a large crewed space expedition visits Halley's Comet in Sir Arthur C.
